Loop on stdin for persistent benchmark protocol.

Rewrap the Haskell entry point `Main_Verified.hs` so that one invocation
of the resulting `svp_verified` binary handles many bench requests,
instead of spawning a fresh process per call. Each line of stdin is one
matrix in `[[Integer]]` Haskell-read syntax; each line of stdout is the
squared norm emitted by `test_verified`. The binary exits cleanly on
EOF.

This is necessary because GHC start-up plus the original per-call
`readFile` is ~22 ms on the audit host, which dominates the wall time
of sub-millisecond LLL inputs and makes the comparator ratio dishonest
under SPEC/benchmarking.md (post-#3657) "External comparators / Process
call".

The Hex-side wiring in `HexLLL/Bench.lean` spawns the driver lazily,
caches the process handle in an `IO.Ref`, sends one request line per
call, and parses one reply line back. On process death the wiring
re-spawns once and retries; persistent failure surfaces as an
`IO.userError`.

--- a/haskell_sources/Main_Verified.hs
+++ b/haskell_sources/Main_Verified.hs
@@ -1,11 +1,15 @@
 {-# LANGUAGE LambdaCase #-}
 module Main(main)
   where
-import System.Environment
+import System.IO
 import LLL_SVP
 
-main = do 
-  as <- getArgs
-  input <- readFile (as !! 0)
-  let mat = (read input :: [[Integer]])
-  putStrLn (show (test_verified mat))
+main = do
+  hSetBuffering stdout LineBuffering
+  contents <- getContents
+  mapM_ runOne (lines contents)
+  where
+    runOne line = do
+      let mat = (read line :: [[Integer]])
+      putStrLn (show (test_verified mat))
+      hFlush stdout
